Dear Peter,

Below is the latest list of errata.  I have also come up against an
incorrect proof that I have not been able to fix and would appreciate
it if you could tell me how to do it correctly.  In your proof that
partial transversals form a matroid (on page 204, part 4), you take
transversals Y,Z with |Y|<|Z| and then consider the sets A_y indexed
by the elements of y and a set B_z indexed by some element of Z.
You then look at X'=Y U z and consider the restrictions of the sets
A_y and B_z to X'.  You then claim that if these sets have an SDR,
then we are done as X' is an SDR of the original family.  This is
false.  What if z is not in Y but B_z = B_y for some y.  Then an SDR
of the restrictions does not lift to a transversal of the original
sets since two of the restrictions correspond to only one of the
originals.  You can fix this by only considering the case when B_z does
not equal any A_y.  But then the second part of your proof goes awry,
as we can only conclude that such z are in Y, not that Z is contained
in Y, and so get no contradiction.  HELP!

-Bruce


