Dear Peter,

Here are yet more errata.  There are also some logical difficulties.

In the proof of Proposition 10.4.3, it seems you could get a better
bound of 2^{(l-1)/2} for l>=2 as follows.  You get the count of
{n choose l} 2/2^{l choose 2} as before and then use l!>=2 and
n(n-1)...(n-l+1)<n^l to get that this is bounded above by
n^l/2^{l choose 2} and now the better bound works.

On page 193, to show that a bijection s of lattices is an
isomorphism, it suffices to prove either that s preserves meet or
join.  You need not do both.  To see this, use the equivalent
definition that s and s^{-1} should be order preserving.  Assume just
that s preserves join.  Then if a <= b we have a v b = b so
s(b) = s(a v b) = s(a) v s(b) so s(a) <= s(b).  On the other hand,
if s(a) <= s(b) then s(b) = s(a) v s(b) = s(a v b) so b = a v b
by injectivity and a <= b.

On the same page, do you really want the first bulleted statement in
the definition of complementation?  It is not in the definitions I've
seen (eg in Stanley's text) and you don't use it in the proof of 12.3.3.

All the best, Bruce

